welfth-century Latin vita of the Welsh saint Dyfrig to the early modernArthur of the Dutch. Topics addressed include the reasons for Edward III's abandonment of the Order of the Round Table; the 1368 relocation of Arthur's tomb at Glastonbury Abbey; the evidence for our knowledge of the French manuscript sources for Malory's first tale, in particular the Suite du Merlin; and the central role played by Cornwall in Malory's literary worldview. Meanwhile, a survey of the pan-European aspects of medieval Arthurian literature, considering key characters in both familiar and less familiar languages such as Old Norse and Hebrew, further outlines its popularity and impact. Elizabeth Archibald is Professor of English, University of Durham;Professor David F. Johnson teaches in the English Department, Florida State University, Tallahassee. Contributors: Dorsey Armstrong, Christopher Berard, Bart Besamusca, P.J.C. Field, Linda Gowans, Sjoerd Levelt, JulianM. Luxford, Ryan Naughton, Jessica Quinlan, Joshua Byron Smith  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArthurian romancesxHistory and criticism. 4aMedieval Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh1 aArchibald, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArchibald, Elizabeth, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aArmstrong, Dorsey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerard, Christopher Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerard, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBesamusca, Bart, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aByron Smith, Joshua, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aField, P. J. C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voca